From: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
Date: Wed, 27 May 2026 17:29:20 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] ==== mm/damon/sysfs: kobject_del() fix =====

mm/damon/sysfs: kobject_del() directories that users can create/remove

DAMON sysfs interface allows users to create and remove arbitrary number
of directories on sysfs, using a few files having 'nr_' prefix.  For
example, 'nr_kdamonds'.  When the user writes a number 'N' to the files,
directories having name starting from '0' to 'N - 1' are created in the
same directory.  The pre-existing number-named directories are all
removed before creating the new directories.

DAMON sysfs interface use only kobject_put() for this.  Because there is
no kernel component that references the directories, this is no problem
in normal situations.  However, if CONFIG_DEBUG_KOBJECT_RELEASE is
enabled, and the user writes a non-zero number to such 'nr_*' files
while there are pre-existing number-named directories, this becomes a
problem.  In this scenario, DAMON sysfs interface decreases the
reference counts of the existing directories and immediately creates new
directories.  Because CONFIG_DEBUG_KOBJECT_RELEASE delays removal of the
sysfs directories, the new directory creation fails due to name
conflicts.

This doesn't cause catastrophic issues like kernel panic or memory
corruption.  Users can work around by removing all directories first
(write 0 to the nr_* files) and then create new directories after
confirming the old directories are gone.  But, still the user experience
is quite bad.  Kernel logs can also be flooded from name conflict error
messages. DAMON selftest for basic sysfs operations (sysfs.sh) also
fails.

Fix the issues by calling kobject_del() first.

The issue was discovered [1] by Sashiko, though the finding was not
completely correct and captured only one instance of the class.

[1] https://lore.kernel.org/20260517205828.6204-1-sj@kernel.org

Signed-off-by: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
